medial rectus muscle","Innervates multiple extraocular muscles","Controls eye elevation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe abducens nerve (cranial nerve VI) \u003Cstrong\u003Einnervates the lateral rectus muscle\u003C/strong\u003E of the eye. This muscle is responsible for abduction - moving the eye laterally (away from the midline). The nerve has a purely motor function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial rectus muscle\u003C/strong\u003E is innervated by the oculomotor nerve (CN III), whilst \u003Cstrong\u003Eeye elevation\u003C/strong\u003E is controlled by the superior rectus muscle (CN III). \u003Cstrong\u003EPupillary constriction\u003C/strong\u003E is controlled by parasympathetic fibres in the oculomotor nerve. The abducens nerve only \u003Cstrong\u003Einnervates one muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - the lateral rectus, not multiple extraocular muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDamage to the abducens nerve results in paralysis of the lateral rectus muscle, causing the affected eye to deviate medially due to unopposed action of the medial rectus muscle. The patient will be unable to abduct the affected eye.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The abducens nerve (cranial nerve VI) innervates only the lateral rectus muscle of the eye.","The lateral rectus muscle is responsible for abduction (lateral movement) of the eye.","Damage to the abducens nerve results in medial deviation of the affected eye and inability to look laterally."],"references":["Azarmina M, Azarmina H. The six syndromes of the sixth cranial nerve. J Ophthalmic Vis Res. 2013 Apr;8(2):160-71. PMID: 23943691; PMCID: PMC3740468.","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u0027s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98541"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16279"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98541"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T19:42:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T19:43:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8970"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116548"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data